name: methylene diphenyl diisocyanate production, ISOPA | methylene diphenyl diisocyanate, ISOPA | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/29487/documentation

This dataset contains pre-allocated industry data from ISOPA (European trade association for producers of diisocyanates and polyols), available at https://plasticseurope.org/sustainability/circularity/life-cycle-thinking/eco-profiles-set/, published in April 2021. ecoinvent cannot guarantee that the upstream and downstream supply chains were linked to the ecoinvent database, while the intermediate exchanges are not maintained with the annual database updates. The respective dataset that is linked to the ecoinvent database value chains has an activity name methylene diphenyl diisocyanate production”.;This dataset represents the average production of 1 kg of methylene diphenyl diisocyanate (MDI). At the same time, the formed hydrochloric acid is treated as a valuable by-product. Even though MDI exists in three isomers, 4.4-MDI is the most widely used in industrial applications and is the one represented in this dataset.;MDI (CAS: 101-68-8) is an aromatic diisocyanate that is used in the production of polyurethane foams in combination with polyols (Boustead 2005). Polyurethane foams show good thermal insulation properties, and thus, are used extensively in the manufacture of freezers and refrigerators, and in building and automotive applications. In 2012 the largest producer of MDI globally was Bayer, producing 1.24 million tonnes per year, followed by Wanhua Group, producing 1.1 million tonnes per year (Gal, 2012).;The industrial preparation of isocyanates is carried out with the reaction of an amine with phosgene in an aromatic solvent. In more detail, the production scheme for MDI can be breakdown into the following chemical reactions:;Methylene dianiline (MDA) production from aniline and formaldehyde: 2C6H7N + CH2O -> C13H14N2+H2O;MDA phosgenation: C13H14N2  + 2COCl2  -> C15H10N2O2  + 4HCl;This dataset is based on industry data from five different MDI producers with six plants in five European countries participated in the primary data collection.;References:;Heino Falcke, Simon Holbrook, Iain Clenahan,Alfredo Lopez Carretero, Teoman Sanalan,;Thomas Brinkmann, Joze Roth, Benoit Zerger; Serge Roudier, Luis Delgado Sancho (2017): Best Available Techniques (BAT) Reference Document for the Production of large Volume Organic Chemicals;2021, ISOPA , Eco-profile of toluene diisocyanate (TDI) and methylene diphenyl diisocyanate (MDI) , 3 - SeparatePublication;G. Margaret Wells, “Handbook of Petrochemicals and Processes”, 2nd edition, Ashgate, 1999;Boustead. 2005. Eco-profiles of the European Plastics Industry Diphenylmethane diisocyanate (MDI). Retrieved from: http://www.polyurethanes.org/uploads/documents/eco_midi.pdf, accessed 26 January 2017;Gal, J. 2012. Wanhua to the rescue of BorsodChem. ICIS Chemical Business. Retrieved from: http://www.icis.com/resources/news/2012/02/20/9533156/wanhua-to-the-rescue-of-borsodchem/, accessed 26 Janury 2017;Christian Six, Frank Richter (2011): Isocyanates, organic, Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Wiley-VCH.

The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.

This activity ends once  the products, i.e., 1 kg of methylene diphenyl diisocyanate and 0.52 kg of hydrochloric acid, are at the production site gate. Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.

processDocumentation.timeDescription: Data collection for production was collected as 12-month averages representing the year 2018. The inventory creation and calculation stage was concluded in 2020, while the technology is not expected to change until 2026.
processDocumentation.geographyDescription: Representative 100% of European (EU-28) production of methylene diphenyl diisocyanate.
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: This inventory represents the average production of methylene diphenyl diisocyanate (MDI), provided as a generic dataset, starting with aniline and formaldehyde as raw materials.;In more detail, the chemical processes involved in the MDI production are described below.;First, methylene dianiline (MDA) is produced through the reaction of formaldehyde with aniline, in the presence of  hydrochloric acid catalyst. As MDI exists in three isomers, a distribution of MDI isomers is obtained, where their share depends on the ratio of aniline to formaldehyde, the acid concentration, and the reaction conditions.;Methylene dianiline (MDA) synthesis: 2C6H7N + CH2O -> C13H14N2+H2O;The mixture at the reactor outlet is neutralised with caustic soda, and separated into an organic phase and an inorganic (aqueous) phase. The latter phase contains the crude MDA isomer mixture, and is washed. Excess amounts of aniline are recovered with distillation and recycled to the MDA synthesis stage. At the same time, the inorganic (aqueous) phase is further purified from any residual organic substance, and subsequently discharged for additional treatment and recovery stages.;The crude MDA isomer mixture is subsequently treated with phosgene to produce an MDI isomer mixture in solution, along with HCl byproduct.;MDA phosgenation: C13H14N2  + 2COCl2  -> C15H10N2O2  + 4HCl;In absence of phosgene in the form of a raw material, this intermediate is produced on-side from carbon monoxide and chlorine.;Phosgene production: CO + Cl2 -->  COCl2;The crude MDI solution is first separated by the solvent, which is recovered via distillation, and subsequently purified through fractional distillation, crystallisation, or sublimation.;Reference(s):;2021, ISOPA , Eco-profile of toluene diisocyanate (TDI) and methylene diphenyl diisocyanate (MDI) , 3 - SeparatePublication
processDocumentation.samplingDescription:
Industry data, representative 100 % of European (EU-28) production capacity, based on production volumes in 2018.

The industrial data used originate from five different MDI producers with six plants, in five European countries.
